## 1. Product Vision

Chi Terminal is a modern, GPU-accelerated terminal emulator for Linux
desktops. It combines the speed of native rendering with the beauty of
Material 3 Expressive design via the Chi QML component library.

It should work perfectly with zero configuration, yet offer deep
customization for power users who want it.

**One sentence**: The terminal that's fast enough you never notice it,
beautiful enough you actually enjoy it, and smart enough it helps you
work.

---

## 2. Design Pillars

| # | Pillar | Meaning |
|---|--------|---------|
| 1 | **Fast by default** | GPU-rendered grid. Instant startup. No perceptible lag, ever. |
| 2 | **Zero-config beauty** | Material 3 theming out of the box. No setup required to look great. |
| 3 | **Keyboard-sovereign** | Every feature accessible without touching a mouse. |
| 4 | **Privacy-first, local-first** | No accounts. No telemetry. No cloud dependency. |
| 5 | **Don't reinvent the wheel** | Use best-in-class libraries for core functionality. |
| 6 | **Progressive disclosure** | Simple surface, deep power underneath. Complexity is opt-in. |

---

## 3. Target Users

| Segment | Description | Priority |
|---------|-------------|----------|
| **Primary** | Developers who live in the terminal daily. They use TUI apps (neovim, lazygit, btop), run build tools, SSH into servers. They care about speed, correctness, and keyboard efficiency. | P0 |
| **Secondary** | System administrators managing remote servers. Multiple SSH sessions, monitoring, log tailing. They need tabs, panes, and session durability. | P1 |
| **Tertiary** | Casual users who want a beautiful, fast default terminal. They run occasional commands and want something that "just works" without configuration. | P2 |

---

## 4. Platform Targets

| Platform | Display Server | Priority | Timeline |
|----------|---------------|----------|----------|
| Linux | Wayland (primary) | P0 | Tier 1 |
| Linux | X11 (supported) | P0 | Tier 1 |
| macOS | Native | P2 | Post Tier 3 |
| Windows | — | P3 | Not in scope |

---

## 5. Tier 1 — Core Terminal (MVP)

> **Goal**: A fully functional, fast, beautiful terminal emulator that
> can replace your daily driver. Rock-solid fundamentals only.

### 5.1 Terminal Emulation

The terminal must be a correct, modern VT emulator. Users should never
encounter broken rendering in any standard tool.

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| VT220 + xterm-256color compatibility | Full escape sequence parsing, passes vttest | P0 |
| True color (24-bit) | 16.7 million colors via SGR sequences | P0 |
| Unicode | Full grapheme cluster segmentation, combining characters | P0 |
| Emoji | Color emoji rendering via system fonts | P0 |
| Wide characters | CJK double-width with correct cursor positioning | P0 |
| Alternate screen buffer | Correct switching for TUI applications | P0 |
| Scrollback buffer | Configurable (default 10,000 lines, option for unlimited) | P0 |
| Bracketed paste | Prevent paste injection attacks (mode 2004) | P0 |
| Hyperlinks | OSC 8 — clickable links emitted by CLI tools | P0 |
| Synchronized rendering | DEC mode 2026 — prevent tearing in TUI apps | P0 |
| Kitty Keyboard Protocol | Modern keyboard encoding for Neovim, etc. | P0 |
| Mouse reporting | All standard modes (1000, 1002, 1003, 1006 SGR) | P0 |
| Text reflow | Soft-wrapped lines reflow when terminal resizes | P0 |

### 5.2 Tabs

Users need multiple terminal sessions organized in tabs. Tab management
must be fast and keyboard-driven.

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Create tab | Keyboard shortcut, button, or context action | P0 |
| Close tab | With confirmation if a process is running | P0 |
| Switch tabs | Next/previous cycling and direct jump (Alt+1-9) | P0 |
| Reorder tabs | Drag-to-reorder with mouse | P0 |
| Tab title | Derived from shell integration (CWD, command, hostname) or process name | P0 |
| Tab bar visibility | Configurable: always, when multiple, never | P0 |
| New tab inherits CWD | New tab opens in same directory as current | P0 |

### 5.3 Split Panes

Users need to see multiple terminals simultaneously without leaving
the window. Splits must be keyboard-driven with smart defaults.

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Vertical split | Divide pane left/right | P0 |
| Horizontal split | Divide pane top/bottom | P0 |
| Navigate between panes | Vim-style directional navigation (H/J/K/L) | P0 |
| Close pane | Close current pane, redistribute space | P0 |
| Zen mode | Maximize/restore any single pane to fill the tab | P0 |
| Auto-layout | System chooses H/V split based on current pane aspect ratio | P0 |
| Resize panes | Keyboard-driven resize in increments | P0 |
| Mouse resize | Thin drag handle between panes with snap points | P0 |
| Predefined layouts | 1-up, 2-column, 2-row, L-shape, grid — accessible via command | P1 |

**Design constraint**: No arbitrary freeform splitter dragging. Pane
boundaries snap to sensible ratios (25/33/50/67/75%). Resize handles
are minimal (4px) and non-intrusive.

### 5.4 Search

Users need to find text in terminal output quickly.

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| In-tab search | Search through current scrollback buffer | P0 |
| Highlight all matches | All matches visually highlighted simultaneously | P0 |
| Navigate matches | Step forward/backward through matches | P0 |
| Regex support | Toggle between plain text and regular expression | P0 |
| Case sensitivity | Toggle case-sensitive search | P0 |
| Match count | Display "N of M" match indicator | P0 |
| Keyboard-only | Open, search, navigate, close — all without mouse | P0 |

### 5.5 Copy, Paste & Selection

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Click-drag selection | Select text region with mouse | P0 |
| Word selection | Double-click selects word | P0 |
| Line selection | Triple-click selects line | P0 |
| Rectangular selection | Alt+click-drag for column selection | P0 |
| Smart Ctrl+C | Copy if text is selected; send SIGINT if not | P0 |
| Explicit copy/paste | Ctrl+Shift+C / Ctrl+Shift+V always work | P0 |
| Bracketed paste | Paste wrapped in bracket sequences for safety | P0 |
| Auto-copy on select | Optional behavior (off by default) | P1 |
| Smart selection | Quad-click selects semantic unit (URL, path, quoted string) | P1 |

### 5.6 Context Menu

The right-click menu must be context-aware — showing different options
based on what's under the cursor.

| Detected Context | Expected Menu Items |
|-----------------|---------------------|
| **Empty area** | Paste, Select All, Clear Terminal, ─, Split Right, Split Down, ─, New Tab |
| **Selected text** | Copy, ─, Search Web, ─, Paste, Select All |
| **URL / Hyperlink** | Open Link, Copy URL, ─, Copy, Paste |
| **File path** | Open File, Open in File Manager, Copy Path, ─, Copy, Paste |

Context detection must handle:
- URLs (http://, https://, ftp://)
- File paths (absolute, relative, ~-prefixed)
- Selected text takes precedence over other detection

### 5.7 Clickable Elements

| Element | Trigger | Action |
|---------|---------|--------|
| URLs | Ctrl+Click or OSC 8 | Open in default browser |
| File paths | Ctrl+Click | Open in default editor or file manager |

Visual treatment: underline appears on Ctrl+hover, cursor changes to
pointer. No underlines without Ctrl held (avoids visual noise).

### 5.8 Font System

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Configurable font family | Default: system monospace | P0 |
| Configurable font size | Default: 13px, range 6-72 | P0 |
| Font ligatures | Enabled by default, configurable | P0 |
| Bold / Italic variants | Auto-detect or user-specified | P0 |
| Zoom | Ctrl+= / Ctrl+- per-tab, Ctrl+0 reset | P0 |
| HiDPI | Correct rendering on high-DPI displays | P0 |

### 5.9 Theming & Colors

Chi Terminal inherits Material 3 Dynamic Color from the Chi library.
Terminal colors derive from the active theme automatically.

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Material 3 integration | Terminal colors derived from ChiTheme tokens | P0 |
| ANSI 16 colors | Configurable per scheme | P0 |
| Dark/Light mode | Follows system or user preference, toggle | P0 |
| Built-in color schemes | Material, Catppuccin, Tokyo Night, Dracula, Nord, Gruvbox | P0 |
| Import schemes | iTerm2, Xresources, TOML formats | P1 |
| Background opacity | 0.0 - 1.0 (requires compositor) | P1 |

**Terminal-to-theme color mapping:**

| Terminal Element | ChiTheme Token |
|-----------------|---------------|
| Background | surfaceContainerLowest |
| Foreground | onSurface |
| Cursor | primary |
| Cursor text | onPrimary |
| Selection background | primaryContainer |
| Selection foreground | onPrimaryContainer |
| URL underline | tertiary |
| Search match background | tertiaryContainer |
| Active search match | primary / onPrimary |

### 5.10 Keyboard Shortcuts

All shortcuts must be user-rebindable with conflict detection.

**Default bindings:**

| Action | Default Binding |
|--------|----------------|
| New tab | Ctrl+Shift+T |
| Close tab/pane | Ctrl+Shift+W |
| Next tab | Ctrl+Tab |
| Previous tab | Ctrl+Shift+Tab |
| Tab 1-9 | Alt+1 through Alt+9 |
| Split vertical | Ctrl+Shift+D |
| Split horizontal | Ctrl+Shift+E |
| Navigate pane left | Ctrl+Shift+H |
| Navigate pane down | Ctrl+Shift+J |
| Navigate pane up | Ctrl+Shift+K |
| Navigate pane right | Ctrl+Shift+L |
| Maximize/restore pane | Ctrl+Shift+Enter |
| Copy | Ctrl+Shift+C |
| Paste | Ctrl+Shift+V |
| Search | Ctrl+Shift+F |
| Command palette | Ctrl+Shift+P |
| Zoom in | Ctrl+Equal |
| Zoom out | Ctrl+Minus |
| Zoom reset | Ctrl+0 |
| Fullscreen | F11 |
| Settings | Ctrl+Shift+Comma |

### 5.11 Configuration

Configuration via TOML file with live reload. No configuration required
for default usage.

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| TOML config file | `$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/chiterm/chiterm.toml` | P0 |
| XDG compliance | Respect XDG Base Directory spec | P0 |
| Sensible defaults | Everything works without a config file | P0 |
| Live reload | Changes apply without restart (most settings) | P0 |
| Validation | Invalid config shows clear error, falls back to defaults | P0 |

**Configurable settings categories:**
- General (shell, TERM, scrollback, bell behavior)
- Font (family, size, ligatures, line height)
- Appearance (theme, color scheme, opacity, cursor style/blink, padding)
- Tabs (bar visibility, position, new tab behavior)
- Keybindings (all rebindable)

### 5.12 Shell Integration

The terminal should understand shell semantics — not just raw byte
streams.

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| CWD tracking | Know current directory per pane (OSC 7) | P0 |
| Command timing | Measure duration of each command (OSC 133) | P0 |
| Exit code detection | Know if last command succeeded/failed (OSC 133) | P0 |
| Process name detection | Detect foreground process for tab title | P0 |
| Auto tab title | Show CWD / running command / hostname | P0 |
| Integration scripts | Ship scripts for bash, zsh, fish | P0 |

### 5.13 Status Bar

A minimal, informational bar at the bottom of each tab.

| Element | Position | Content |
|---------|----------|---------|
| Current directory | Left | CWD icon + truncated path |
| Git branch | Left (if applicable) | Branch icon + name |
| Command duration | Right | Timer icon + duration (when > 1s) |
| Exit indicator | Right | ✓ (success) or ✗ (failure) |

The status bar must be:
- Compact (≤ 24px height)
- Non-intrusive (muted colors, small typography)
- Hideable via config

---

## 6. Tier 2 — Power Features

> **Goal**: Features that elevate Chi Terminal from "good terminal" to
> "can't go back to anything else." Productivity, session management,
> and desktop integration.

### 6.1 Block-Based Output

Commands and their output are grouped as discrete "blocks" — the
single biggest UX innovation in modern terminals.

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Command grouping | Each command + its output is a navigable block | P1 |
| Block header | Shows command text, timestamp, duration | P1 |
| Block actions | Copy output, re-run command, collapse — on hover | P1 |
| Per-block search | Search within a single command's output | P1 |
| Collapse/expand | Hide verbose completed output, expand on demand | P1 |
| Block navigation | Keyboard shortcut to jump between blocks | P1 |

**Depends on**: Shell integration (OSC 133) from Tier 1.

**Design constraint**: Blocks are a UI overlay on the scrollback buffer,
not a replacement. When shell integration is unavailable (e.g. SSH
into a machine without integration scripts), the terminal degrades
gracefully to a standard continuous scrollback.

### 6.2 Command Palette

A unified fuzzy-search launcher for all terminal actions.

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Fuzzy search | Match against all registered actions | P1 |
| Action categories | Tabs, Panes, Theme, Layout, Settings, Commands | P1 |
| Recent commands | Quick re-run from shell history | P1 |
| Keyboard-only | Full navigation without mouse | P1 |
| Extensible | Tier 3 plugins can register actions | P1 |

### 6.3 Session Persistence & Workspaces

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Auto-save on exit | Save window state, tabs, pane layouts, CWDs | P1 |
| Auto-restore on launch | Reconstruct full session tree | P1 |
| Named workspaces | User-defined workspace profiles ("Backend", "DevOps") | P1 |
| Workspace switching | Via command palette or keybinding | P1 |

### 6.4 Quake-Mode Dropdown

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Global hotkey | System-wide shortcut (default: F12) | P1 |
| Slide animation | Smooth reveal from top of screen | P1 |
| Auto-hide on focus loss | Configurable behavior | P1 |
| Independent session | Separate tab/pane state from main window | P1 |

### 6.5 Desktop Integration

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Long-running command notification | Desktop notification when command exceeding threshold completes | P1 |
| Notification threshold | Configurable (default: 10 seconds) | P1 |
| Urgency hint | Set WM urgency flag when notification fires | P1 |
| Drag-and-drop | Drag files into terminal to paste paths | P1 |
| D-Bus integration | Linux desktop notifications and shortcuts | P1 |

### 6.6 Image Protocol Support

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Kitty graphics protocol | Display images inline in terminal | P1 |
| Sixel graphics | Legacy protocol, widely supported by tools | P1 |
| iTerm2 inline images | OSC 1337 protocol | P2 |

### 6.7 Tab Enhancements

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Color-coded tabs | Auto-tint by context (SSH, root, local) | P1 |
| Tab preview on hover | Thumbnail tooltip of terminal content | P1 |
| Pin tabs | Persistent, non-closeable tabs | P1 |
| Drag tab to pane | Drag a tab into a split to create a new pane | P1 |

### 6.8 Cross-Tab Search

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Search all sessions | Global search across all open tabs | P1 |
| Results grouped by tab | Show which tab contains each match | P1 |
| Navigate to match | Click result to jump to the tab and position | P1 |

### 6.9 Smart Selection

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| URL detection | Full URL including query parameters | P1 |
| Path detection | Absolute and relative paths | P1 |
| Quoted strings | Single and double quoted text | P1 |
| IP addresses | IPv4 and IPv6 | P1 |
| Email addresses | Standard format | P1 |
| Quad-click trigger | Smart-select the detected semantic unit | P1 |
| Context menu binding | Right-click on detected element shows relevant actions | P1 |

### 6.10 Settings GUI

A graphical settings panel built entirely with Chi components.

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| All Tier 1 settings | Accessible via GUI | P1 |
| Live preview | Changes visible immediately | P1 |
| Font preview | Show sample text in selected font/size | P1 |
| Color scheme preview | Visual preview of each scheme | P1 |
| Keybinding editor | Rebind with conflict detection | P1 |
| Search settings | Filter/find specific settings | P1 |

---

## 7. Tier 3 — Advanced & AI

> **Goal**: Differentiating features. AI assistance, rich widgets,
> and extensibility. What makes Chi Terminal unique.

### 7.1 AI Assistant Panel

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Natural language → command | Describe what you want, get the command | P2 |
| Error explanation | Select an error, get plain-English explanation | P2 |
| Context-aware chat | AI can read terminal output (with explicit consent) | P2 |
| Insert suggestion | One-click to paste AI-suggested command into terminal | P2 |

**AI backend support:**

| Backend | Type | Priority |
|---------|------|----------|
| Ollama | Local, self-hosted | P2 (first-class) |
| llama.cpp | Local, embedded | P2 |
| OpenAI API | Cloud, user API key | P2 |
| Anthropic API | Cloud, user API key | P2 |
| Custom endpoint | User-configured URL | P3 |

**Privacy requirements:**
- Terminal content is NEVER sent to any cloud service without explicit
  user action per interaction
- Each "send to AI" shows exactly what data will be transmitted
- Local models work fully offline — first-class, not second-class
- API keys stored in system keyring (not plaintext config)
- No Chi Terminal account required, ever

### 7.2 SSH Bookmark Manager

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Save connections | Host, port, user, identity file, jump host | P2 |
| Quick connect | From command palette or dedicated panel | P2 |
| Auto profile switching | Tab color and title change on SSH connection | P2 |
| SSH config integration | Read from `~/.ssh/config` | P2 |

### 7.3 Inline Widgets

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Markdown preview | Render .md files inline | P2 |
| System monitor | CPU/memory mini-graphs in a side widget | P2 |
| Git status widget | Branch, staged/unstaged changes, ahead/behind | P2 |
| File preview | Syntax-highlighted file content on action | P2 |

### 7.4 Triggers & Automation

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Regex triggers | Match patterns in terminal output | P2 |
| Actions | Notify, highlight, run command, play sound | P2 |
| Profile auto-switching | Change appearance by hostname, directory, or command | P2 |

### 7.5 Extension API

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| Plugin loading | Load QML-based extensions | P3 |
| Event hooks | onCommandStart, onCommandEnd, onDirectoryChanged, etc. | P3 |
| Custom widgets | Third-party status bar items, side panels | P3 |
| Custom context menu items | Plugins can extend right-click menus | P3 |
| Custom command palette actions | Plugins can register commands | P3 |

---

## 8. Performance Budget

These are hard requirements, not aspirations. Every commit must
maintain these numbers.

| Metric | Target | How to Measure |
|--------|--------|----------------|
| Cold startup to first frame | < 100ms | `time chiterm --benchmark-startup` |
| Warm startup (FS cached) | < 50ms | Second consecutive launch |
| Input latency (keypress → pixel) | < 8ms | TYPOMETER or high-speed camera |
| `cat` large file throughput | > 500 MB/s | `cat` 1GB file, time to completion |
| Full screen redraw (80×24) | < 1ms | Internal frame timing |
| Full screen redraw (200×50) | < 3ms | Internal frame timing |
| Frame rate during fast scroll | Sustained 60 FPS | `QSG_RENDER_TIMING=1` |
| Memory — idle, 1 tab | < 30 MB RSS | `ps aux` / `smem` |
| Memory — per additional tab | < 15 MB RSS | Delta measurement |
| Memory — 10K scrollback × 200 cols | < 50 MB | `smem` per session |
| Config hot reload | < 50ms | Internal timing |

---

## 9. Acceptance Criteria

### 9.1 Tier 1 Acceptance

The MVP is complete when ALL of the following pass:

**Emulation correctness:**
- [ ] Launches default `$SHELL` and interacts normally
- [ ] Passes vttest basic compatibility suite
- [ ] True color gradient test renders correctly
- [ ] All common TUI apps render correctly: vim, neovim, tmux, htop,
      lazygit, btop, midnight commander
- [ ] tmux inside Chi Terminal works fully (nested multiplexer)
- [ ] Unicode test suite: combining characters, ZWJ emoji, CJK wide chars
- [ ] Kitty Keyboard Protocol test passes (Neovim `set keyprotocol`)

**Feature completeness:**
- [ ] Tabs: create, close, switch (cycle + direct), reorder via drag
- [ ] Splits: create H/V, navigate all 4 directions, close, zen mode
- [ ] Search: open, type, highlight matches, navigate, regex mode, close
- [ ] Copy/paste: selection, Ctrl+Shift+C/V, smart Ctrl+C, bracketed paste
- [ ] Context menu: correct items for empty area, selected text, URL, file path
- [ ] Ctrl+click on URL opens browser
- [ ] Ctrl+click on file path opens editor/file manager
- [ ] Font zoom: Ctrl+=, Ctrl+-, Ctrl+0
- [ ] Scrollback: mouse wheel, Shift+PageUp/Down
- [ ] Config file loads, validates, and applies
- [ ] Config hot reload works for colors, fonts, opacity, keybindings
- [ ] Shell integration: CWD shown in status bar, command timing, exit codes
- [ ] Tab title updates from CWD / running process
- [ ] All default keybindings work
- [ ] Custom keybindings apply from config

**Performance:**
- [ ] Startup < 100ms
- [ ] `cat` throughput > 500 MB/s
- [ ] No visible tearing in Neovim during fast scrolling
- [ ] 60 FPS maintained during `yes` output flood

**Edge cases:**
- [ ] Graceful handling of missing config file (use defaults)
- [ ] Graceful handling of invalid config (error message + defaults)
- [ ] Close confirmation when process is running
- [ ] Terminal resizes correctly with reflow
- [ ] Works under both Wayland and X11

### 9.2 Tier 2 Acceptance

- [ ] Blocks: commands visually grouped, collapsible, with actions
- [ ] Blocks degrade gracefully without shell integration
- [ ] Command palette: opens, fuzzy searches, executes actions
- [ ] Session saves on exit, restores on launch (tabs, panes, CWDs)
- [ ] Workspaces: create, name, switch, delete
- [ ] Quake mode: global hotkey toggles dropdown terminal
- [ ] Desktop notification fires for long-running commands
- [ ] Kitty graphics protocol displays images inline
- [ ] Tab colors change automatically on SSH / root
- [ ] Cross-tab search finds and navigates to results
- [ ] Smart selection detects URLs, paths, quoted strings
- [ ] Settings GUI allows editing all Tier 1 settings with live preview

### 9.3 Tier 3 Acceptance

- [ ] AI panel: send query, receive response, insert command
- [ ] AI works fully offline with Ollama
- [ ] AI never sends data to cloud without explicit per-interaction consent
- [ ] SSH bookmarks: save, quick-connect, auto-profile
- [ ] At least one inline widget functional (markdown or sysinfo)
- [ ] Triggers: define regex → action, fires on match
- [ ] Extension: load a sample QML plugin that adds a status bar item

---

## 10. Non-Goals & Anti-Patterns

Things we explicitly **will not** build:

| Anti-Pattern | Reason |
|-------------|--------|
| Heavy animations on terminal content | Terminals must feel instant; Chi motion tokens are for UI chrome only |
| Mandatory cloud account | Privacy-first; never gate features behind sign-up |
| Built-in text editor | We are not competing with vim/nano/helix; preview only |
| Custom shell or prompt | Always use the user's shell; never override their environment |
| Electron or web-tech rendering | Performance and memory are non-negotiable |
| Arbitrary freeform splitter dragging | Smart layouts with snap points instead |
| Feature overload at launch | Progressive disclosure; Tier 2/3 features are discoverable, not forced |
| Trying to replace tmux | Respect tmux users; provide convenience splits, not session resilience |

---

## 11. Reference Terminals Studied

| Terminal | Key Lesson |
|----------|-----------|
| **Ghostty** | Zero-config philosophy; embeddable VT library; native-first |
| **Warp** | Block-based output innovation; AI integration patterns; shows cloud account risk |
| **Wave** | Widget system; privacy-respecting AI with user API keys |
| **Kitty** | Graphics protocol (de facto standard); performance benchmark |
| **WezTerm** | Lua extensibility model; configuration-as-code |
| **Alacritty** | Speed benchmark; simplicity philosophy; what minimalism looks like |
| **iTerm2** | Smart selection depth; shell integration features; trigger system |
| **Windows Terminal** | Settings GUI patterns; profile system; tab UX |

---

*This specification is the product contract. It defines WHAT we build
and HOW we know it's done. It does not define HOW we build it — that
belongs in `architecture.md`.*

*Last updated: March 2026*
