Markdown

# Chi Terminal — Implementation Notes
# Version 0.1.0 | March 2026

> Evolving notes on implementation details, optimization strategies,
> and technical decisions. This document changes frequently and is NOT
> a contract. Anything here can be revised based on profiling and
> real-world testing.

---

## Table of Contents

1. [Cell Memory Layout](#1-cell-memory-layout)
2. [Glyph Atlas Strategy](#2-glyph-atlas-strategy)
3. [PTY I/O Tuning](#3-pty-io-tuning)
4. [Scrollback Ring Buffer](#4-scrollback-ring-buffer)
5. [Dirty Tracking Strategy](#5-dirty-tracking-strategy)
6. [Scene Graph Node Structure](#6-scene-graph-node-structure)
7. [Font Handling Details](#7-font-handling-details)
8. [Reflow Algorithm](#8-reflow-algorithm)
9. [Smart Selection Patterns](#9-smart-selection-patterns)
10. [Profiling Methodology](#10-profiling-methodology)
11. [Known Challenges & Open Questions](#11-known-challenges--open-questions)

---

## 1. Cell Memory Layout

**Goal**: Keep Cell as small as possible. Every byte matters when you
have 200 cols × 10,000 scrollback lines = 2,000,000 cells.

**Current thinking** (subject to profiling):
Cell { codepoint : char32_t (4 bytes) — primary character fg : uint32_t (4 bytes) — RGBA, 0 = default bg : uint32_t (4 bytes) — RGBA, 0 = default flags : uint16_t (2 bytes) — packed attributes hyperlinkId : uint16_t (2 bytes) — 0 = none underlineColor : uint32_t (4 bytes) — separate color } Total: 20 bytes per cell

text


**flags bitfield (16 bits):**
bit 0 : bold bit 1 : italic bit 2 : underline bit 3 : strikethrough bit 4 : blink bit 5 : inverse bit 6 : invisible bit 7 : faint bit 8 : overline bit 9-10 : underline style (single/double/curly/dotted) bit 11-12 : width (0=continuation, 1=normal, 2=wide) bit 13-15 : reserved

text


**Combining characters**: Stored in a separate side table
(`HashMap<CellPosition, Vec<char32_t>>`) to avoid bloating every
Cell. Less than 1% of cells have combining characters.

**Memory estimate:**
- 80×24 visible: 38.4 KB
- 200 cols × 10K scrollback: ~40 MB
- 200 cols × 100K scrollback: ~400 MB (this is where unlimited gets expensive)

**Open question**: Should we compress scrollback rows that are far off-screen?
Candidates: run-length encoding for cells with identical attributes.

---

## 2. Glyph Atlas Strategy

**Starting parameters** (will tune based on GPU memory and hit rates):

- Initial atlas size: 1024×1024, RGBA8
- Growth: double to 2048×2048 if needed, then 4096×4096 max
- Pre-cache: ASCII 32-126 in regular, bold, italic, bold+italic = ~380 entries
- On-demand: cache misses render the glyph and insert
- Eviction: LRU eviction when atlas is full (rare in practice)

**Glyph hash key**: `(codepoint, bold, italic, font_size_tenths)` — this
means font zoom creates new atlas entries. Acceptable since zoom is rare.

**Emoji handling**: System emoji font renders through a separate path.
Color emoji are stored as RGBA in the atlas. May need a separate atlas
to avoid polluting the grayscale glyph texture. TBD after testing.

**Subpixel rendering**: Follow system FreeType settings. This affects
atlas format (RGB subpixel needs 3x width). Start with grayscale,
add subpixel if users demand it.

---

## 3. PTY I/O Tuning

**Read side:**
- QSocketNotifier on master FD (edge-triggered on Linux via epoll)
- Read in chunks — start with 16 KB, profile and adjust
- Feed to VtBridge.feed() immediately — avoid extra copy
- Goal: minimize latency between PTY output and screen update

**Write side:**
- Small writes (individual keypresses) are common: 1-6 bytes
- Coalesce writes within the same event loop tick via a write buffer
- Flush write buffer on event loop idle (QTimer::singleShot(0, ...))
- This avoids excessive syscalls during paste operations

**Resize:**
- `ioctl(masterFd, TIOCSWINSZ, &ws)` — synchronous, fast
- Must be followed by VtBridge.resize() and ScreenBuffer.resize()
- Reflow happens in ScreenBuffer.resize()

**Foreground process detection:**
- `tcgetpgrp(masterFd)` → PID of foreground process group
- `/proc/{pid}/comm` → process name
- Poll periodically (every 500ms) or on SIGCHLD equivalent
- Used for: tab title, close confirmation

---

## 4. Scrollback Ring Buffer

**Structure:**
RingBuffer<Row>

capacity: configurable (default 10,000 rows)
head: index of newest row
tail: index of oldest row (head - count + 1, mod capacity)
Row = array<Cell, cols> (dynamically sized)
text


**On scroll up** (new content pushes visible area):
- Top visible row moves into scrollback (append to ring)
- If ring is full, oldest row is evicted (overwritten)

**On resize wider**: Rows need reflow. See §8.

**Unlimited scrollback**: Use a growable vector instead of ring buffer.
Monitor memory usage and warn user if exceeding threshold.

---

## 5. Dirty Tracking Strategy

**Granularity**: Per-row, not per-cell.

**Rationale**: Most VT operations dirty entire rows (line clear, scroll,
insert/delete line). Per-cell tracking adds overhead with minimal
rendering savings. A typical redraw touches 1-5 rows.

**Implementation**: Bitset of N rows. Set on any mutation. Checked and
cleared by the renderer each frame.

**Full-dirty events**: Resize, color scheme change, font change, scroll
position change → mark all rows dirty.

---

## 6. Scene Graph Node Structure
QSGNode (root) ├── QSGSimpleRectNode (terminal background) ├── QSGNode (cell rows group) │ ├── RowNode (row 0) │ │ ├── QSGSimpleRectNode (bg for cells with non-default bg) │ │ └── QSGImageNode (textured quads for glyphs) │ ├── RowNode (row 1) │ │ └── ... │ └── RowNode (row N) ├── QSGNode (selection overlay) │ └── QSGSimpleRectNode (semi-transparent selection rects) ├── QSGNode (search match highlights) │ └── QSGSimpleRectNode (per match) ├── QSGNode (cursor) │ └── QSGSimpleRectNode or QSGImageNode └── QSGNode (link underlines) └── QSGGeometryNode (underline lines)

text


**Update strategy in `updatePaintNode()`:**
1. Check dirty rows from ScreenBuffer
2. For each dirty row: rebuild that RowNode's children
3. Update cursor node position
4. Update selection overlay if selection changed
5. Update search highlights if results changed
6. Clean: ~O(dirty_rows 

This is not just good — it’s dangerously close to implementation, and that’s both its strength and its flaw.

I’m going to be direct, because this level of project needs precision:

Verdict: High-quality hybrid (Spec + Architecture + Partial Implementation)
You didn’t write a pure spec.
You wrote a systems blueprint.

That’s powerful—but you need to control it.

What you did exceptionally well
1. Requirements are strong and explicit
You nailed what most people fail at:

Clear feature tiers (T1 / T2 / T3)
Priority tagging (P0, P1, P2)
Measurable performance targets
Acceptance criteria (this is elite-level spec work)
This alone makes the project executable.

2. Architecture is extremely well defined
This is not vague:

Scene graph decision ✔
Glyph atlas strategy ✔
Split tree model ✔
VT abstraction ✔
Someone competent could start building immediately.

3. You eliminated ambiguity
There are almost no “what do they mean?” gaps.

That’s rare. And valuable.

Where this goes wrong (and it will if you don’t fix it)
1. You leaked too much implementation into the spec
Examples:

Full C++ class definitions (PtyManager, VtBridge)
QML component structures
Exact internal fields (uint16_t flags : 10)
File structure
This is not spec territory anymore.

Why this is dangerous:
Locks you into early decisions
Makes refactoring expensive
Prevents architectural evolution
Turns spec into something that gets outdated quickly
2. You mixed 3 different documents into one
Right now this file is:

Product spec
System architecture doc
Partial implementation reference
That’s why it feels “complete”—but also rigid.

3. Some parts are prematurely optimized
Example:

Exact memory layout of Cell
Glyph atlas size (2048x2048)
Read buffer sizes
These belong in:
→ design docs or performance notes, not the core spec

What this SHOULD be split into
If you want this to scale like a serious system, break it cleanly:

1. spec.md (Product Contract)
Keep:

Features (Tier 1/2/3)
Requirements tables
Acceptance criteria
Performance targets
UX behavior
Remove:

All code
Most structs/classes
Internal architecture details
2. architecture.md (System Design)
Move here:

Scene graph strategy
VT bridge design
Split tree system
Rendering pipeline
Module boundaries
Keep diagrams — they’re excellent.

3. interfaces.md (Contracts)
Keep:

Clean API definitions (simplified)
No implementation details
Example (good):

C++

interface TerminalBackend {
    feed(data)
    resize(rows, cols)
    getCell(row, col)
}
Example (bad — what you have now):

C++

uint16_t combiningCount : 4;
4. implementation_notes.md (Optional, evolving)
Put here:

Memory layouts
Buffer sizes
Optimization tricks
Experimental decisions
This can change freely without breaking the spec.

What to fix immediately (high impact)
Strip or move these from spec.md:
All full C++ class definitions
QML component code
File structure tree
Bitfield-level structs
Build system details
What you should KEEP exactly as is
These are top-tier:

Tier system (T1/T2/T3)
Acceptance criteria checklist
Performance budget table
Design pillars
Feature requirement tables
That’s your real spec.

Final judgment
You’re operating at a level where most projects fail not because of lack of detail—but because of too much rigidity too early.

Right now:

You can build this immediately ✅
But you’re also locking yourself into decisions you haven’t tested yet ⚠️
Bottom line
This is better than 95% of specs
But it’s not cleanly structured as a spec
With proper separation, it becomes elite-level engineering documentation
If you want, I’ll restructure this into a clean, production-grade spec + architecture split without losing any of your depth.

