Markdown

# Chi Terminal — Technical Specification
# Version 0.1.0 | March 2026

> A modern, GPU-accelerated terminal emulator built on Qt 6 / QML with
> the Chi Material 3 Expressive UI library. Designed to be fast by default,
> beautiful without configuration, and powerful through progressive disclosure.

---

## Table of Contents

1. [Project Overview](#1-project-overview)
2. [Design Pillars](#2-design-pillars)
3. [Technology Stack](#3-technology-stack)
4. [Tier 1 — Core Terminal (MVP)](#4-tier-1--core-terminal-mvp)
5. [Tier 2 — Power Features](#5-tier-2--power-features)
6. [Tier 3 — Advanced & AI](#6-tier-3--advanced--ai)
7. [Project Structure](#7-project-structure)
8. [Build System](#8-build-system)
9. [Performance Budget](#9-performance-budget)
10. [Testing Strategy](#10-testing-strategy)
11. [Appendices](#11-appendices)

---

## 1. Project Overview

Chi Terminal is a desktop terminal emulator for Linux (X11 + Wayland)
that combines the speed of GPU-accelerated rendering with the beauty
of Material 3 Expressive design, using the Chi QML component library
for all UI chrome.

### 1.1 Target Platforms

| Platform | Priority | Display Server       |
|----------|----------|----------------------|
| Linux    | P0       | Wayland (primary), X11 (supported) |
| macOS    | P2       | Future consideration |
| Windows  | P3       | Not in scope for MVP |

### 1.2 Target Users

- **Primary**: Developers who live in the terminal daily
- **Secondary**: System administrators managing remote servers
- **Tertiary**: Casual users who want a beautiful, fast default terminal

---

## 2. Design Pillars

1. **Fast by default** — GPU-rendered terminal grid, instant startup (<100ms)
2. **Zero-config beauty** — Chi Material 3 theming out of the box, no setup
3. **Keyboard-sovereign** — Every feature accessible without a mouse
4. **Privacy-first, local-first** — No accounts, no telemetry, no cloud dependency
5. **Don't reinvent the wheel** — Use best-in-class libraries for core functionality
6. **Progressive disclosure** — Simple surface, deep power underneath

---

## 3. Technology Stack

### 3.1 Core Dependencies

| Component              | Library / Tool              | Version   | License     | Rationale |
|------------------------|-----------------------------|-----------|-------------|-----------|
| **UI Framework**       | Qt 6 (Quick, Core, GUI)     | ≥ 6.5     | LGPLv3      | Chi library requirement; QML for declarative UI |
| **UI Components**      | Chi UI Library              | 1.0       | —           | Material 3 Expressive; zero-config theming |
| **Terminal Emulation** | libghostty-vt (C API)       | HEAD/alpha| MIT         | Best-in-class VT emulation, SIMD-optimized, proven by millions of Ghostty users |
| **Terminal Emulation (Fallback)** | libvterm (Leonerd) | 0.3.x     | MIT         | Stable C99 VT220/xterm library as fallback if libghostty C API isn't ready |
| **PTY Management**     | POSIX `forkpty()` / custom  | —         | System      | Direct PTY via `<pty.h>` — thin C++ wrapper |
| **Config Parsing**     | toml++ (tomlplusplus)       | 3.4+      | MIT         | Header-only C++17 TOML parser; used by Qt Creator internally |
| **Font Rendering**     | Qt's font engine + FreeType | System    | —           | Qt handles font shaping via HarfBuzz internally |
| **Build System**       | CMake                       | ≥ 3.19    | BSD         | Industry standard; FetchContent for deps |
| **Compiler**           | GCC 13+ / Clang 16+        | —         | —           | C++17 minimum; C++20 preferred |
| **Zig Toolchain**      | Zig                         | 0.15.x    | MIT         | Required to build libghostty-vt from source |

### 3.2 Library Decisions — Deep Rationale

#### Terminal Emulation: libghostty-vt (Primary) + libvterm (Fallback)

The terminal emulation layer is the single most critical dependency.
We **do not** write our own VT parser.

**libghostty-vt** is the primary choice:
- Extracted directly from the Ghostty terminal emulator, which has
  millions of daily active users proving its correctness
- Zero-dependency (not even libc required), SIMD-optimized parsing,
  leading Unicode support, fuzz-tested
- Provides VT sequence parsing, terminal state management (cursor,
  styles, text reflow, scrollback), and renderer state management
- C API is under active development with a work-in-progress public API;
  dozens of projects are already building on it
- The Ghostty team has separated libghostty's release cycle from the
  GUI application, targeting a tagged release soon
- Handles hard problems we'd otherwise need to solve: Kitty Keyboard
  Protocol encoding, Kitty Graphics Protocol parsing, proper Unicode
  grapheme clustering, synchronized rendering

**libvterm** (Leonerd's version) is the fallback:
- Abstract C99 library implementing VT220/xterm emulation
- No graphics toolkit dependency — uses callback function pointers
- Avoids malloc() during normal operation (embedded-friendly)
- Well-established, used by Neovim's built-in terminal
- Serves as our safety net if libghostty's C API timeline slips

**Migration path**: Start with libvterm for immediate development velocity.
Integrate libghostty-vt once its C API stabilizes. Both use a callback
architecture, so our rendering bridge adapts cleanly.

#### Why NOT other terminal libraries:

| Library       | Why Not |
|---------------|---------|
| QTermWidget   | GPL-licensed, Qt Widgets-based (not QML), heavy Konsole heritage |
| yat           | VT100 only, Qt 5.10, unmaintained |
| literm        | Minimal, unmaintained, Qt Quick but limited emulation |
| VTE (GNOME)   | GTK-specific, not embeddable in Qt |
| xterm.js      | JavaScript/browser — wrong platform |

#### Config: toml++ (tomlplusplus)

- Header-only C++17, MIT-licensed
- Full TOML v1.0 compliance with opt-in v1.1 features
- Supports serialization back to TOML, JSON, and YAML
- Used internally by Qt Creator (as toml11)
- Can disable parser or formatters independently to reduce binary size
- Exception-free mode available (`TOML_EXCEPTIONS 0`)

Alternative considered: **Erbsland Qt TOML** — Qt-native TOML parser,
LGPL, excellent Qt integration. Viable if we want tighter Qt type
integration (returns QStrings), but toml++ is lighter and MIT.

### 3.3 System Dependencies (Linux)
Build dependencies
qt6-base-dev qt6-declarative-dev qt6-shadertools-dev cmake ninja-build gcc/g++ (or clang) zig (0.15.x, for libghostty-vt compilation)

Runtime dependencies
libgl1 / mesa (for Qt Quick Scene Graph GPU rendering) fontconfig, freetype2, harfbuzz (via Qt)

text


---

## 4. Tier 1 — Core Terminal (MVP)

> **Goal**: A fully functional, fast, beautiful terminal emulator that
> can replace your daily driver. No bells and whistles — just rock-solid
> fundamentals.

### 4.1 Terminal Emulation Engine

#### 4.1.1 Requirements

| Requirement | Detail | Priority |
|-------------|--------|----------|
| VT220 + xterm-256color | Full escape sequence parsing | P0 |
| True color (24-bit) | SGR 38;2;r;g;b / 48;2;r;g;b | P0 |
| Unicode support | Full grapheme cluster segmentation, combining chars | P0 |
| Emoji rendering | Color emoji via system fonts | P0 |
| Wide characters | CJK double-width, correct cursor positioning | P0 |
| Alternate screen | Modes 47, 1047, 1049 with correct switching | P0 |
| Scrollback buffer | Configurable size (default 10,000 lines, max unlimited) | P0 |
| Bracketed paste | Mode 2004 — prevent paste injection attacks | P0 |
| OSC 8 hyperlinks | Clickable links emitted by CLI tools | P0 |
| Synchronized rendering | DEC mode 2026 — prevents tearing in TUI apps | P0 |
| Kitty Keyboard Protocol | Modern keyboard encoding for Neovim, etc. | P0 |
| Mouse reporting | Modes 1000, 1002, 1003, 1006 (SGR) | P0 |
| Text reflow on resize | Soft-wrapped lines reflow when terminal resizes | P0 |

#### 4.1.2 Architecture
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐ │ QML UI Layer (Chi) │ │ TabBar │ Panes │ ContextMenu │ SearchOverlay │ StatusBar │ ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤ │ TerminalWidget (QQuickItem) │ │ ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐ │ │ │ Custom QQuickItem subclass │ │ │ │ - Renders terminal grid via Qt Scene Graph │ │ │ │ - Texture atlas for glyph caching │ │ │ │ - Selection rectangle overlay │ │ │ │ - Cursor rendering (block/beam/underline) │ │ │ └────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘ │ ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤ │ Terminal Bridge (C++) │ │ ┌──────────────┐ ┌──────────────┐ ┌────────────────┐ │ │ │ PTY Manager │ │ VT Engine │ │ Screen Buffer │ │ │ │ │ │ (libghostty │ │ (ring buffer │ │ │ │ forkpty() │ │ or libvterm)│ │ + scrollback) │ │ │ │ read/write │ │ │ │ │ │ │ │ poll/epoll │ │ parse() │ │ cells[] │ │ │ │ │ │ callbacks │ │ dirty flags │ │ │ └──────────────┘ └──────────────┘ └────────────────┘ │ ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤ │ Operating System │ │ PTY (pseudoterminal) │ Shell Process │ └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

text


#### 4.1.3 PTY Management (C++ Module)

```cpp
// PtyManager.h — thin RAII wrapper around POSIX PTY
class PtyManager : public QObject {
    Q_OBJECT
public:
    bool spawn(const QString &shell, const QStringList &args,
               const QProcessEnvironment &env,
               const QString &workingDir,
               int rows, int cols);
    void write(const QByteArray &data);
    void resize(int rows, int cols);  // TIOCSWINSZ
    void close();

    pid_t childPid() const;
    pid_t foregroundPid() const;  // tcgetpgrp()
    int masterFd() const;

signals:
    void dataReceived(const QByteArray &data);
    void processExited(int exitCode);

private:
    int m_masterFd = -1;
    pid_t m_childPid = -1;
    QSocketNotifier *m_readNotifier = nullptr;  // epoll-backed
};
Key implementation details:

Use forkpty() for PTY creation (from <pty.h>)
QSocketNotifier on the master FD for async read notification
Read buffer: 64KB ring buffer, read in 16KB chunks
Write coalescing: buffer writes and flush on next event loop tick
Signal handling: SIGCHLD for child exit detection
TIOCSWINSZ ioctl for terminal resize
4.1.4 VT Engine Bridge
C++

// VtBridge.h — abstraction over terminal emulation backend
class VtBridge : public QObject {
    Q_OBJECT
public:
    enum class Backend { LibGhostty, LibVterm };

    explicit VtBridge(Backend backend, int rows, int cols);

    void feed(const char *data, size_t len);  // feed PTY data
    void resize(int rows, int cols);

    // Screen state queries
    const Cell &cellAt(int row, int col) const;
    CursorState cursor() const;
    bool isDirty() const;
    DirtyRegion dirtyRegion();  // returns and clears
    int scrollbackLines() const;

    // Input encoding
    QByteArray encodeKey(Qt::Key key, Qt::KeyboardModifiers mods);
    QByteArray encodeMouse(MouseEvent event);

signals:
    void
 
 (const DirtyRegion &region);
    void bellRung();
    void titleChanged(const QString &title);
    void iconTitleChanged(const QString &title);
    void cursorStyleChanged(CursorStyle style);
    void hyperlinkDetected(const QString &url, const QRect &region);
    void clipboardRequested(const QString &data);  // OSC 52
};
4.2 GPU-Accelerated Rendering
4.2.1 TerminalWidget (QQuickItem)
The terminal grid is rendered as a custom QQuickItem using Qt's Scene Graph API directly — NOT using QML Text elements (which would create thousands of QObjects and destroy performance).

C++

// TerminalWidget.h
class TerminalWidget : public QQuickItem {
    Q_OBJECT
    QML_ELEMENT

    Q_PROPERTY(int rows READ rows NOTIFY sizeChanged)
    Q_PROPERTY(int cols READ cols NOTIFY sizeChanged)
    Q_PROPERTY(QFont font READ font WRITE setFont NOTIFY fontChanged)
    Q_PROPERTY(qreal cellWidth READ cellWidth NOTIFY fontChanged)
    Q_PROPERTY(qreal cellHeight READ cellHeight NOTIFY fontChanged)

protected:
    QSGNode *updatePaintNode(QSGNode *oldNode,
                             UpdatePaintNodeData *data) override;

private:
    // Glyph atlas: single large texture with all rendered glyphs
    GlyphAtlas m_glyphAtlas;

    // Dirty tracking: only re-render changed cells
    QBitArray m_dirtyCells;

    // Double-buffered screen state
    ScreenBuffer m_front, m_back;
};
4.2.2 Glyph Atlas Strategy
text

┌─────────────────────────────┐
│  Glyph Atlas Texture        │
│  (2048x2048, RGBA8)         │
│                              │
│  ┌──┬──┬──┬──┬──┬──┬──┬──┐ │
│  │A │B │C │…│a │b │c │…│ │ │  ← ASCII (pre-cached)
│  ├──┼──┼──┼──┼──┼──┼──┼──┤ │
│  │① │② │…│  │  │  │  │  │ │  ← On-demand glyphs
│  ├──┼──┼──┼──┼──┼──┼──┼──┤ │
│  │🔥│📁│…│  │  │  │  │  │ │  ← Emoji / wide chars
│  └──┴──┴──┴──┴──┴──┴──┴──┘ │
└─────────────────────────────┘

Each cell rendered as a textured quad in the Scene Graph:
- Position: (col * cellWidth, row * cellHeight)
- Texture coords: lookup from atlas hash map
- Color: uniform per-cell (fg, bg, attributes)
Performance targets:

Glyph cache hit rate > 99% for typical usage
Full screen redraw (80x24): < 1ms
cat /dev/urandom sustained: > 1 GB/s throughput
Scrollback navigation: 60 FPS
4.2.3 Cell Data Structure
C++

struct Cell {
    char32_t codepoint;          // 4 bytes — primary character
    uint16_t combiningCount : 4; // up to 15 combining characters
    uint16_t width : 2;          // 0, 1, or 2 (wide char)
    uint16_t flags : 10;         // bold, italic, underline, etc.

    uint32_t fg;                 // RGBA foreground (0 = default)
    uint32_t bg;                 // RGBA background (0 = default)
    uint32_t underlineColor;     // separate underline color

    uint16_t hyperlinkId;        // 0 = no hyperlink

    // Combining characters stored separately in a side table
    // to keep Cell size small (18 bytes typical)
};

// Target: Cell fits in 20 bytes
// 80x24 screen = 38,400 bytes ≈ 37.5 KB
// 10,000 line scrollback @ 200 cols = 40 MB (acceptable)
