4.4 Split Pane System
4.4.1 Requirements
Feature	Detail	Priority
Vertical split	Ctrl+Shift+D	P0
Horizontal split	Ctrl+Shift+E	P0
Navigate panes	Ctrl+Shift+H/J/K/L (vim-style)	P0
Close pane	Ctrl+Shift+W (if >1 pane)	P0
Maximize/restore pane	Ctrl+Shift+Enter (zen mode)	P0
Auto-layout	Choose H/V split based on aspect ratio	P0
Predefined layouts	1-up, 2-col, 2-row, L-shape, grid	P1
4.4.2 Architecture: Recursive Split Tree
C++

// SplitNode.h — binary tree structure for pane layout
struct SplitNode {
    enum Type { Leaf, HSplit, VSplit };

    Type type;
    double ratio = 0.5;  // split ratio (0.0 - 1.0)

    // If Leaf:
    TerminalSession *session = nullptr;

    // If Split:
    std::unique_ptr<SplitNode> first;
    std::unique_ptr<SplitNode> second;

    // Computed geometry (set during layout pass)
    QRectF geometry;
};
The split tree is rendered in QML via a recursive Loader pattern:

qml

// SplitView.qml
Item {
    required property var node  // SplitNode from C++

    Loader {
        active: node.type === SplitNode.Leaf
        sourceComponent: TerminalPane { session: node.session }
    }

    Loader {
        active: node.type !== SplitNode.Leaf
        sourceComponent: SplitContainer {
            orientation: node.type === SplitNode.HSplit
                         ? Qt.Horizontal : Qt.Vertical
            ratio: node.ratio
            first: SplitView { node: node.first }
            second: SplitView { node: node.second }
        }
    }
}
No arbitrary drag-to-resize splitters. Instead:

Keyboard: Ctrl+Shift+Alt+H/J/K/L to resize in increments
Mouse: thin (4px) drag handle between panes, snap to 25/33/50/67/75%
Predefined layouts accessible via command palette
