B. Key Technical Decisions Log
Decision	Choice	Alternatives Considered	Rationale
VT backend	libghostty-vt + libvterm fallback	QTermWidget, VTE, custom	Best-in-class quality, C API, zero deps, proven by Ghostty
Config format	TOML (toml++)	YAML, JSON, INI, KConfig	Human-readable, typed, industry trend (Cargo, Ghostty, etc.)
UI framework	QML + Chi	Qt Widgets, GTK4	Required by spec (Chi library), declarative, GPU-friendly
Rendering	QQuickItem + Scene Graph	QPainter, raw OpenGL	Qt-integrated GPU rendering, correct in both X11/Wayland
No Electron	—	Electron + xterm.js	Performance, memory, native feel
No custom shell	User's $SHELL	Custom prompt	Never override user's environment
C. Reference Terminals Studied
Terminal	Key Takeaway for Chi Terminal
Ghostty	Zero-config philosophy; libghostty-vt as embeddable core
Warp	Block-based output; AI integration patterns
Wave	Widget system; privacy-respecting AI with user API keys
Kitty	Graphics protocol (de facto standard); performance bar
WezTerm	Lua extensibility; cross-platform config
Alacritty	Performance benchmark; simplicity philosophy
iTerm2	Smart selection; shell integration depth; triggers
Windows Terminal	Settings UI patterns; profile system
D. Glossary
Term	Definition
PTY	Pseudoterminal — OS-level pair of file descriptors (master/slave)
VT	Virtual Terminal — escape sequence protocol (VT100/VT220/xterm)
OSC	Operating System Command — escape sequences for metadata
SGR	Select Graphic Rendition — escape sequences for text styling
DCS	Device Control String — escape sequence category
Scene Graph	Qt Quick's retained-mode rendering tree (GPU-backed)
Glyph Atlas	Single texture containing all rendered font glyphs
Scrollback	Buffer of lines that have scrolled off the visible area
Block	Grouped command + output treated as a single object
Shell Integration	Scripts that emit OSC sequences from the shell prompt
This specification is a living document. Update as decisions are made and implementation reveals new requirements.

